<!-- Map & Set -->

<!-- (1)Map (Key-Value Store) -->
-Similar to an object, but keys can be any type (objects, functions, primitives).
-Maintains insertion order.
-Provides built-in methods for iteration and size checking.

Key Methods:
    -.set(key, value) → add entry
    -.get(key) → get value
    -.has(key) → check existence
    -.delete(key) → remove key
    -.clear() → remove all
    -.size → number of entries

<!-- (2)Set (Unique Values Collection) -->
-Stores only unique values.
-Order is preserved.
-Great for removing duplicates.

Key Methods:
    -.add(value) → insert value
    -.has(value) → check existence
    -.delete(value) → remove
    -.clear() → remove all
    -.size → number of elements


<!-- (3)Differences vs Objects & Arrays -->
-Objects → keys must be string/symbol; Map allows any type.
-Arrays → duplicates allowed; Set enforces uniqueness.
-Map/Set have better performance for frequent additions/deletions.